<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-435-356  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 435 356.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Federal Computer Week  July 17 1989 v3 n29 p20(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Air Force: don't weaken AFCAC, SSC in reordering. (Air ForceComputer Acquisitions Center; Air Force Standard Systems Center)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Page, Donald.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The Air Force plans to combine its two major computer procurementoffices, the Air Force Computer Acquisitions Center (AFCAC) inMassachusetts and the Air Force Standard Systems Center (SSC) inAlabama, into a single Computer Systems Division.andP;  The two centershave successfully completed such complex acquisitions as a 1983microcomputer contract with Zenith Data Systems and a 1988AFCAC-251 contract for multiuser computers.andP;  A General ServicesAdministration review report says that the Air Force has ledinitiatives of standardizing requirements contracts, that itsacquisition process is clear and well documented, and that itmakes effective provision for new technology.andP;  The reportidentified the lack of formal guidance in central selectionactivities as an area of concern.andP;  If the new Computer SystemsDivision is not committed to AFCAC's proven capabilities, thecenter could be weakened considerably.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     MilitaryDefense ContractsInformation SystemsReorganizationUnited States. Air ForceCommand and Control SystemsManagement of EDP.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>